Crude Oil Volatility Slips as Futures Rise on Fed Speculation

-- B y   M a r g o t   H a b i b y
-- 
2011-08-23T18:18:58Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-23/crude-oil-volatility-slips-as-futures-rise-on-fed-speculation.html
Crude oil options volatility slipped
as the underlying futures rose for a second day in  New York  amid
speculation the  Federal Reserve  will bolster efforts to
stimulate the economy.  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
October, a measure of expected price swings in futures and a
gauge of options prices, was 41.8 percent at 1 p.m. in New York,
down from 45.7 percent yesterday. Options volatility was 38.3
percent a week ago.  Oil for October delivery climbed 76 cents, or 0.9 percent,
to $85.18 a barrel at 2 p.m. on the  New York Mercantile
Exchange . Prices have fallen 6.8 percent this year.  The most active contract in electronic trading today was
October $80 puts, with 2,282 lots changing hands at of 1:51 p.m.
The options tumbled 63 cents to $1.89 a barrel. October $65
puts, the next-most active option, lost 11 cents to 23 cents
with 1,896 lots trading. One contract covers 1,000 barrels of
crude.  The exchange distributes real-time data for electronic
trading and releases information on floor trading, where the
bulk of options trading occur the next business day.  December $80 puts were the most active options traded in
the previous session, with 4,511 lots changing hands. They fell
82 cents to $5.29 a barrel. The next-most active options,
December $70 puts, declined 51 cents to $2.52 a barrel on volume
of 4,200.  Open interest was highest for December $100 calls with
47,809 contracts. Next were December $70 puts with 42,958 and
December $120 calls with 42,700.  To contact the reporter on this story:
